doc/source/developer_resources/config_vi.message:
Many of the designers I know have been unable to get their VirtualBox configuration to work at all reliably with NAT network configuration (including me). My recommendation is to install a separate VM to use as a router instead. I would prefer that we don't document the NAT network option as it is just going to cause frustration.

Here are the instructions I use:

A router can be used to act as a gateway to allow your other Virtual Box VMs (e.g. controllers) access to the external internet. The router needs to be able to forward traffic from the OAM network to the internet.

In Virtual Box, create a new Linux VM to act as your router (e.g. running ubuntu). You can get a ubuntu iso (for ease-of-use download Ubuntu 18.04 Desktop version or higher) from our internal mirror at http://yow-mirror.wrs.com/mirror/ubuntu.com/ubuntu-releases. *Installation tip: Before you install the Ubuntu 18.04 Desktop version in a Virtual Box 5.2, configure the VM as follows: "Shut down the VM and Edit Settings: (1) Go to Display and move the "Video memory" slider all the way to the right, then also tick "Acceleration" checkbox "Enable 3D Acceleration", (2) Go to General/Advanced and set "Shared Clipboard" and "Drag'n Drop" to Bidirectional, (3) Go to User Interface/Devices and select "Devices/Insert Guest Additions CD image" from the drop down. Restart  your VM.*

The instructions below all work with ubuntu.

The network configuration for this VM must include:

A NAT interface to allow installation and access to the external internet
A Host-only Adapter connected to the same network as the OAM interfaces on your controllers
Once the router VM has been installed, enable forwarding. In ubuntu do the following:

# Edit sysctl.conf and uncomment the following line:
# net.ipv4.ip_forward=1
sudo vim /etc/sysctl.conf
# Activate the change
sudo sysctl -p
Then add the gateway IP address to the interface connected to the OAM host only network:

# Assuming that enp0s8 is connected to the OAM host only network:
cat > /etc/netplan/99_config.yaml << EOF
network:
  version: 2
  renderer: networkd
  ethernets:
    enp0s8:
      addresses:
        - 10.10.10.1/24
EOF
sudo netplan apply

# If netplan is not installed on your router you can use these commands instead of the above.
ip addr add 10.10.10.1/24 dev enp0s8

Finally, set up iptables to forward packets from the host only network to the NAT network:

# This assumes the NAT is on enp0s3 and the host only network is on enp0s8
sudo iptables -t nat -A POSTROUTING --out-interface enp0s3 -j MASQUERADE
sudo iptables -A FORWARD --in-interface enp0s8 -j ACCEPT
sudo apt-get install iptables-persistent
